        <!-- Page header -->
        <div class="docs-page-header">
            <span class="docs-badge">Documentation</span>
            <h1 class="docs-title">How UniCore Works</h1>
            <p class="docs-subtitle">
                UniCore connects people who need compute power with people who have hardware to spare —
                through a secure relay that keeps both sides private.
            </p>
        </div>

        <!-- What is UniCore -->
        <section id="what-is-unicore" class="docs-section">
            <h2>What is UniCore?</h2>
            <p>
                UniCore is a peer-to-peer distributed computing marketplace. Instead of paying
                a cloud provider like AWS or GCP for a virtual machine, you rent compute time
                directly from other people's idle hardware — at a fraction of the cost.
            </p>
            <p>
                If you have a spare PC, you can list it on UniCore and earn money whenever
                someone uses it. If you need a Linux VM for a build job, a dev environment,
                or a quick experiment, you can spin one up in seconds from your browser —
                no account setup, no port forwarding, no exposed IP addresses.
            </p>

            <div class="docs-callout docs-callout-cyan">
                <p class="docs-callout-title">The core insight</p>
                <p>
                    Most personal computers sit idle more than 90% of the time. UniCore lets
                    that idle capacity do useful work for someone else, and pays the owner for it.
                </p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Architecture -->
        <section id="architecture" class="docs-section">
            <h2>Architecture</h2>
            <p>
                UniCore uses a three-tier relay model. Neither the consumer nor the provider
                ever exposes a public IP address — all traffic flows through a GCP-hosted relay.
            </p>

            <div class="docs-arch-diagram">
                <div class="arch-node arch-node-cyan">
                    <span class="arch-node-label">Consumer</span>
                    <span class="arch-node-sub">Browser</span>
                </div>
                <div class="arch-arrow">&harr;</div>
                <div class="arch-node arch-node-purple">
                    <span class="arch-node-label">GCP Relay</span>
                    <span class="arch-node-sub">SignalR + FRP</span>
                </div>
                <div class="arch-arrow">&harr;</div>
                <div class="arch-node arch-node-green">
                    <span class="arch-node-label">Provider</span>
                    <span class="arch-node-sub">Desktop App</span>
                </div>
                <div class="arch-arrow">&harr;</div>
                <div class="arch-node arch-node-green">
                    <span class="arch-node-label">Docker</span>
                    <span class="arch-node-sub">Linux Container</span>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="docs-steps">
                <div class="docs-step">
                    <span class="docs-step-num step-color-green">1</span>
                    <div>
                        <p class="docs-step-title">Provider registers</p>
                        <p class="docs-step-body">
                            The provider installs the desktop app, authenticates, and connects
                            to the relay via an outbound WebSocket. Their machine appears as
                            available in the marketplace. No inbound firewall rules needed.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="docs-step">
                    <span class="docs-step-num step-color-cyan">2</span>
                    <div>
                        <p class="docs-step-title">Consumer requests a VM</p>
                        <p class="docs-step-body">
                            The consumer visits the web app, picks an available provider, and
                            clicks "Launch VM." The relay forwards this request to the chosen
                            provider's desktop app via SignalR.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="docs-step">
                    <span class="docs-step-num step-color-purple">3</span>
                    <div>
                        <p class="docs-step-title">Container starts, tunnel opens</p>
                        <p class="docs-step-body">
                            The provider app creates a Docker container running Ubuntu and opens
                            an FRP tunnel back through the relay. The relay assigns a public
                            subdomain (e.g. <code>abc123.unicore.app</code>) mapped to that
                            container's SSH port.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="docs-step">
                    <span class="docs-step-num step-color-cyan">4</span>
                    <div>
                        <p class="docs-step-title">Consumer gets a terminal</p>
                        <p class="docs-step-body">
                            The web app opens an in-browser terminal over that subdomain. The
                            consumer has a full Linux shell. The provider's real IP is never
                            disclosed — traffic exits through the GCP relay only.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Getting a VM -->
        <section id="get-a-vm" class="docs-section">
            <h2>Getting a VM</h2>
            <p>
                Consumers access UniCore entirely through a browser — nothing to install.
            </p>

            <ol class="docs-ol">
                <li>Open the UniCore web app and sign in (or continue as guest).</li>
                <li>Browse the list of online providers. Each listing shows available RAM, CPU cores, and current pricing.</li>
                <li>Click <strong>Launch VM</strong> on a provider you want to use.</li>
                <li>Wait a few seconds while the container starts and the tunnel is established.</li>
                <li>A terminal opens in your browser. You're now inside a Ubuntu Linux environment.</li>
                <li>When you're done, click <strong>Stop VM</strong>. Billing stops immediately.</li>
            </ol>

            <div class="docs-callout docs-callout-green">
                <p class="docs-callout-title">No SSH client required</p>
                <p>
                    The terminal runs directly in your browser via a web-based SSH client.
                    You don't need PuTTY, OpenSSH, or any other tool.
                </p>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Terminal Access -->
        <section id="terminal-access" class="docs-section">
            <h2>Terminal Access</h2>
            <p>
                Every VM provisioned through UniCore comes with:
            </p>
            <ul class="docs-ul">
                <li>Ubuntu 22.04 LTS base image</li>
                <li>Full <code>sudo</code> access inside the container</li>
                <li>Outbound internet access (for installing packages, cloning repos, etc.)</li>
                <li>A pre-generated SSH keypair — no password prompt</li>
                <li>Isolated filesystem — your data is not visible to the provider</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
                Sessions are terminated automatically when you close the browser tab or when
                the provider's machine goes offline. Data is not persisted between sessions
                unless you explicitly push it to an external service (GitHub, S3, etc.).
            </p>
        </section>

        <!-- Becoming a Provider -->
        <section id="become-a-provider" class="docs-section">
            <h2>Becoming a Provider</h2>
            <p>
                Anyone with a spare Windows or Linux machine can become a provider. The minimum
                requirements are modest — most gaming PCs, home servers, and old workstations
                qualify.
            </p>

            <div class="docs-specs-grid">
                <div class="docs-spec-card">
                    <p class="docs-spec-label">Minimum RAM</p>
                    <p class="docs-spec-value">4 GB</p>
                </div>
                <div class="docs-spec-card">
                    <p class="docs-spec-label">Minimum CPU</p>
                    <p class="docs-spec-value">2 cores</p>
                </div>
                <div class="docs-spec-card">
                    <p class="docs-spec-label">OS</p>
                    <p class="docs-spec-value">Win 10+ / Ubuntu 20.04+</p>
                </div>
                <div class="docs-spec-card">
                    <p class="docs-spec-label">Required Software</p>
                    <p class="docs-spec-value">Docker Desktop</p>
                </div>
            </div>

            <ol class="docs-ol">
                <li>Download the UniCore Provider app for your platform.</li>
                <li>Install Docker Desktop if you don't already have it.</li>
                <li>Sign in with your UniCore account and complete provider onboarding.</li>
                <li>Set your resource limits — how much RAM and CPU each consumer VM can use.</li>
                <li>Set your price per hour (denominated in USD).</li>
                <li>Click <strong>Go Online</strong>. Your machine is now listed in the marketplace.</li>
            </ol>

            <p>
                You can go offline any time. Active consumer sessions are given a 60-second
                warning before your machine disconnects to give them time to save work.
            </p>
        </section>

        <!-- Earning & Payouts -->
        <section id="earning" class="docs-section">
            <h2>Earning &amp; Payouts</h2>
            <p>
                Providers are paid per hour of active consumer usage. Billing is prorated to
                the minute — consumers are never charged for idle time after their session ends.
            </p>

            <div class="docs-callout docs-callout-green">
                <p class="docs-callout-title">Consistency score</p>
                <p>
                    UniCore tracks provider uptime with a <strong>consistency score</strong> (0–1).
                    Every 10 seconds, a background service checks whether your active VMs are
                    reachable. Being reliably online improves your score and increases your
                    visibility in the marketplace. Going offline unexpectedly reduces it.
                </p>
            </div>

            <p>
                Payouts are processed on a rolling basis. Minimum payout threshold and payment
                methods are configured in your provider dashboard.
            </p>
        </section>

        <!-- Security Model -->
        <section id="security" class="docs-section">
            <h2>Security Model</h2>

            <div class="docs-security-grid">
                <div class="docs-security-card">
                    <p class="docs-security-title">Provider IP never exposed</p>
                    <p class="docs-security-body">
                        Providers connect outbound to the relay via WebSocket. Consumers only
                        ever see the relay's IP. A provider's home or office IP is never
                        transmitted to or visible by consumers.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="docs-security-card">
                    <p class="docs-security-title">Docker isolation</p>
                    <p class="docs-security-body">
                        Each consumer session runs inside a Docker container. Consumers cannot
                        access the provider's host filesystem, processes, or network interfaces
                        outside the container.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="docs-security-card">
                    <p class="docs-security-title">Firebase JWT auth</p>
                    <p class="docs-security-body">
                        All API calls are authenticated with short-lived Firebase JWTs. Tokens
                        are verified server-side on every request. Sessions expire and require
                        re-authentication.
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="docs-security-card">
                    <p class="docs-security-title">GCP-backed relay</p>
                    <p class="docs-security-body">
                        The relay runs on GCP Cloud Run with a Redis backplane for SignalR.
                        Traffic between the relay and both parties is encrypted in transit
                        via TLS.
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <!-- FAQ -->
        <section id="faq" class="docs-section">
            <h2>FAQ</h2>

            <div class="docs-faq">
                <details class="docs-faq-item">
                    <summary>Do consumers need to create an account?</summary>
                    <p>
                        Guest access is available for short sessions. A free account is required
                        to access billing, save session history, or run sessions longer than
                        30 minutes.
                    </p>
                </details>
                <details class="docs-faq-item">
                    <summary>What happens if the provider goes offline mid-session?</summary>
                    <p>
                        The relay detects the disconnection within seconds. The consumer's
                        terminal will display a connection-lost message. Any unsaved work inside
                        the container is lost. UniCore's heartbeat service monitors active VMs
                        every 10 seconds and updates provider consistency scores accordingly.
                    </p>
                </details>
                <details class="docs-faq-item">
                    <summary>Can I run GPU workloads?</summary>
                    <p>
                        GPU passthrough is on the roadmap. Currently, only CPU-based workloads
                        are supported. Providers with CUDA-capable GPUs will be able to opt in
                        to GPU listings in a future release.
                    </p>
                </details>
                <details class="docs-faq-item">
                    <summary>Is my data private from the provider?</summary>
                    <p>
                        All consumer workloads run inside Docker containers. Providers cannot
                        inspect the container filesystem or processes during a live session.
                        However, as with any shared compute environment, you should avoid
                        processing highly sensitive credentials or data you wouldn't trust
                        to a third-party VPS.
                    </p>
                </details>
                <details class="docs-faq-item">
                    <summary>How is pricing set?</summary>
                    <p>
                        Providers set their own hourly rate. UniCore takes a small platform fee.
                        The consumer-facing price shown in the marketplace is the all-in price
                        including the platform fee.
                    </p>
                </details>
                <details class="docs-faq-item">
                    <summary>What ports are available in a consumer VM?</summary>
                    <p>
                        VMs have full outbound internet access. Inbound port exposure (e.g. for
                        running a web server accessible from outside) is not currently supported
                        in the base tier. Public HTTPS subdomain exposure for web development
                        is planned as a future feature.
                    </p>
                </details>
            </div>
        </section>

    </article>
</div>
